TITLE: Variable Mapping in Mastra Workflows (TypeScript)
DESCRIPTION: This snippet demonstrates how to use variable mapping to define data flow between steps in a Mastra workflow. It uses the `Step` and `Workflow` classes from `@mastra/core/workflows` and `zod` for schema definition. The `fetchUserStep` provides data which is mapped to `sendEmailStep` input variables.
SOURCE: https://github.com/mastra-ai/mastra/blob/main/docs/src/content/ja/docs/workflows/control-flow.mdx#_snippet_13

LANGUAGE: typescript
CODE:
```
import { Step, Workflow } from "@mastra/core/workflows";
import { z } from "zod";

const fetchUserStep = new Step({
  id: "fetchUser",
  outputSchema: z.object({
    userId: z.string(),
    name: z.string(),
    email: z.string(),
  }),
  execute: async () => {
    return {
      userId: "user123",
      name: "John Doe",
      email: "john@example.com"
    };
  },
});

const sendEmailStep = new Step({
  id: "sendEmail",
  inputSchema: z.object({
    recipientEmail: z.string(),
    recipientName: z.string(),
  }),
  execute: async ({ context }) => {
    const { recipientEmail, recipientName } = context.inputData;

    // Send email logic here
    return {
      status: "sent",
      to: recipientEmail
    };
  },
});

const workflow = new Workflow({
  name: "email-workflow",
});

workflow
  .step(fetchUserStep)
  .then(sendEmailStep, {
    variables: {
      // Map specific fields from fetchUser to sendEmail inputs
      recipientEmail: { step: fetchUserStep, path: 'email' },
      recipientName: { step: fetchUserStep, path: 'name' }
    }
  })
  .commit();
```

